-- LVMH, Hermes, Alstom, EDF, Peugeot, Air France-KLM: French Equity Preview
-- B y   H e l e n e   F o u q u e t   a n d   A l e x i s   X y d i a s
-- 2010-10-25T06:50:36Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-24/lvmh-hermes-alstom-edf-peugeot-air-france-klm-french-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in Paris today.
Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names. Share
prices are from the last close.  France’s CAC 40 Index lost 0.3 percent to 3,868.54 in
Paris. The SBF 120 Index slid 0.2 percent to 2,884.46.  Air France-KLM Group  (AF FP): The airline’s KLM unit is
lowering prices of flights to European destinations, De
Telegraaf reported, citing KLM Director Bram Graber. In the
Netherlands, KLM and its Transavia.com unit compete with
airlines including EasyJet Plc, the Dutch newspaper said today.
The shares added 1.5 percent to 13.05 euros.  Alstom SA  (ALO FP): The company said the group it runs with
Bombardier Inc. will build 468 subway cars for the Montreal
transit authority. Alstom’s share of the Montreal car order is
345 million euros ($484.8 million) and Bombardier’s share 519
million euros, according to an e-mailed statement. The shares
added 1.3 percent to 37.83 euros.       Atos Origin SA  (ATO FP): The company will achieve an
operating margin of 7 percent to 8 percent by the end of 2011,
Chief Executive Officer  Thierry Breton  told daily La Tribune in
an interview. The shares rose 0.9 percent to 34.34 euros.       Burelle SA  (BUR FP): The company forecast that 2010 sales
will rise 30 percent to 3.2 billion euros. Sales growth will
continue in 2011, the company said in a statement on Hugin. The
stock was unchanged at 161 euros.  Catering International & Services SA  (CTRG FP): The
catering-services group said third-quarter sales climbed to 54
million euros from 39.1 million euros a year earlier. The
company said it sees full-year sales rising at least 10 percent.
The shares remained unchanged at 57.90 euros.  Electricite de France SA  (EDF FP): Constellation Energy
Group Inc. said  Daniel Camus  resigned as the designated director
of EDF International SA on the board effective as of Oct. 21.
Constellation named  Samuel Minzberg  to fill the vacancy. The
shares rose 0.1 percent to 31.87 euros.  Hermes International SCA  (RMS FP):  LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis
Vuitton SA  (MC FP), the world’s largest maker of luxury goods,
said it intends to raise its stake in Hermes International SCA
to 17 percent after buying 14 percent. LVMH doesn’t plan on
taking control of its rival. Hermes’s shares jumped 2.1 percent
to 176.20 euros. LVMH’s shares retreated 0.8 percent to 113.30
euros.  PSA Peugeot Citroen  (UG FP): The French carmaker plans to
boost the number of employees at its research and development
center in Shanghai as it seeks to enter China’s high-end car
market, said  Gregoire Olivier , the president of the French
automaker’s Asia division. The shares increased 2.8 percent to
29.60 euros.       Rhodia SA  (RHA FP): The chemicals company aims to double
its sales in Asia to 2 billion euros a year by 2015, Les Echos
reported, citing Chief Executive Officer  Jean-Pierre Clamadieu .
The shares rose 1.6 percent to 20.16 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
